	Document(content="Note: For Part 8 of Problem 2, there were questions about how to process the 'GOOG.csv', and how to plot the graph. Here are some clarifications. For Part 8, same preprocessing steps used for 'APPL.csv' should be applied to 'GOOG.csv'. Thus, the code provided in 'regularize-cv.py', containing 7 steps for processing the 'APPL.csv' file, can be used again for the 'GOOG.csv' file. When fitting the 'GOOG.csv' file, target variable and feature vectors should be the following: 1) Target variable 'y' is generated by shifting the values in Close column by 1. 2) Attribute vectors correspond to all the remaining columns in 'GOOG.csv', except for the Close column and the Date column. (The procedure is the same as when the 'APPL.csv' file was processed.) When drawing a plot in Part 8, just plot target variable, y , and predicted value, y_hat . There is no need to explicitly designate the labels for x and y axes. For example, it is recommended to use the below code block to generate the plot. ''' plt.figure() plt.plot(y_hat, label='prediction') plt.plot(y, label='actual') plt.legend(fontsize=10, loc='upper left') plt.title('Google Test') plt.show() ''' The title of the plot can be anything. It does not necessarily have to be 'Google Test' as given in the code block above. However, the label of true target_variable and the predicted target_variable should be clearly named so that we can recognize which plot corresponds to which value. ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Important notice on Homework 7', 'timestamp': '2022-10-27T16:05:55Z', 'user': 'l70jr826ufr9d', 'tags': ['hw7', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 245}),
