	Document(content="Question: Can someone explain part C and part D for this question? I get that we have to use the Bayes Theorem, but how is P(G2|X) = 0? Answer: Yes, you can use the formula as shown in the slides and used in the solution or see that it is over 3 standard deviations away from one of the means, thus making it less likely that the point came from that cluster. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring2022Exam3 Q3', 'timestamp': '2022-12-12T20:53:41Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 113}),
	Document(content="Question: In the exam3 review slides, slide 18, why do we only have two values in the numerator for $$\mu_1$$ whereas $$\mu_2$$ has five? Answer: The rest of the likelihoods are just 0 so 0 times the number is just 0 so it is not shown. For other sections, this example was in the GMM slides. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'GMM slide question', 'timestamp': '2022-12-12T20:09:26Z', 'user': 'keuahk7t7pc1oq', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 101}),
	Document(content="Question: Shouldn't the answer be c^t + a^t/2 (c^t - 2)? d(l(c))/dt has a negative out front from the chain rule? Answer: it says gradient descent, so the formula you should use is the c^t - a^td/d(c^t)(l(c^t)) the negative cancel out so it is positive.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F21 Exam3 Q6e', 'timestamp': '2022-12-12T20:03:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 109}),
