	Document(content="Question: For part b, how to draw the graph. I’m able to find the x and y coordinates of highest point of cluster 1 and 2, but how do we draw the rest part. Answer: To draw a normal distribution, make sure the peak of the bell curve is at the mean and the width is consistent with the variance (as mentioned in the student's answer above) ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q 3', 'timestamp': '2022-12-11T23:42:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 116}),
	Document(content="Question: Can somebody explain why odds increase when feature x2 decreases? I thought P(y=1 | x) / P(y=0 | x) is just exp(B0 + B1x1 + ... BmXm) so wouldn't either feature's increase cause an increase in odds? Thanks in advance! Answer: It depends on the coefficient of each feature. The odds are given by: $$\frac{P(y = 1 | x)}{P(y = 0 | x)} = exp({\beta}_0+{\beta}_1x_1+{\beta}_2x_2 + ... + {\beta}_mx_m)$$ Let's say you increase some feature $$ x_j $$ by 1 unit. The ratio of the odds gives you an idea of if the odds have increased or decreased if you increase that feature. The ratio of the odds will be given by: $$\frac{odds(x_j + 1)}{odds(x_j)} = exp(b_j)$$ If the coefficient of the feature j, $$ b_j $$, is negative, the ratio of the odds is lesser than 1 (which means that the odds have decreased). So, when the coefficient of a feature is negative, then an increase in the feature leads to the decrease in odds. Similarly, when $$ b_j $$ is positive, the ratio of odds is positive, meaning that the odds have increased when the feature has been increased. Hope this helps! ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 21 Exam 3 Q6c', 'timestamp': '2022-12-11T22:47:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
	Document(content="Question: For part B, the blank template puts 14 in the denominator across all 3 rows, but has 13 in the denominator for the latter 2 rows in the answer key. Which is the correct one and can someone explain why? Thanks! Answer: The solution is correct. Look at @463 ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 3 Fall 21 Q5', 'timestamp': '2022-12-11T22:32:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 112}),
	Document(content="Question: On the Purdue final exam website it says that the final exam is 2 hours long. I was just double checking to see if this was true or if our exam is only an hour and five minutes like the other two? Answer: This is the default Purdue Policy. Our exam is 65 min long tomorrow ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Final Exam Clarification', 'timestamp': '2022-12-11T21:28:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 4, 'views': 122}),
	Document(content="Question: This question was asked a week ago in this post @425, but no one answered it, and I'm still confused how these coefficients came about. I'd really appreciate if someone could explain how to get the coefficients in front of alpha. Answer: Just in case anyone was still wondering this, this is what I did to solve. fb(x) is going to be 1/ (1 + e^-(1+1(0)+(-2*.5))) which is 1 / (1 + 1) which is just 0.5. Then for each new coefficient, it's: B(0, t+1) = B(0) + fb(x) * a => B(0, t+1) = 1 + 0.5a B(1, t+1) = B(1) + fb(x) * x1 * a => B(1, t + 1) = 1 + 0.5 * 0 * a = 1 B(2, t + 1) = B(2) + fb(x) *x2 * a => B(2, t+1) = -2 +0.5 *0.5 * a = -2 +0.25a ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 3 Fall 2021 6D (again)', 'timestamp': '2022-12-11T20:35:55Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 4, 'views': 130}),
