	Document(content="Question: My method to addressing the question in Path 2 Part 2 was to perform a linear regression analysis on the average values for each student to predict the average overall score. I tested my regression function on some of the stock data and it worked effectively, however when I use the student data the analysis cannot make accurate predictions at all. Is it a possible conclusion that this method cannot predict the proper outcome? If not, how should I approach this better? Answer: It is possible to conclude that a method is not effective as long as you justify how you determined this and why you chose to use the methods you used. It might be helpful to investigate and ensure that the predictions cannot be accurate with this method, and that the poor predictions were not a result of errors. ", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Path 2 Part 2 Interesting Output', 'timestamp': '2022-12-08T18:00:47Z', 'user': 'ktnb8htey833ka', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 92}),
