	Document(content="Question: I was able to do step 2 and 3 for path 1, but the first part of it has really got me stumped. Originally I was going to do a linear regression model and check for predictivity with hypothesis testing, but then I realized each bridge is going to have predictivity since they all have amounts of bikers that sum to the total. I was wondering if anyone has suggestions on a method of figuring out which bridges are best suited for getting the best overall traffic. Answer: The way you mentioned (using regression models) is certainly one of the ways you can go about solving the problem. As the student answer suggested, you might want to look at a visual representation of your data first (either grouped by day, or bridge, or both). There is no 'correct' method to do any of the paths of the mini-project and your method should be based on the data you are given as well as backed up by evidence and reasoning (and you can show this in your write-up). ", meta={'folders': ['project'], 'title': 'Path 1 Part 1', 'timestamp': '2022-12-05T02:09:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['project', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 122}),
