	Document(content="Question: I was running the confusing matrix code which worked perfectly fine with my own inputs. However, when I ran the homwork file after all the work is done, I got the following error. 'TypeError: list indices must be integers or slices, not str' seems like I'm getting this message when the input for confusion matrix is in strings. Any helps on this? I tried to use label enconding to solve this but it wasnt successful as well. Answer: You might want to look into typecasting the input into a 64-bit int (int64) using numpy.astype ( https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.astype.html ) ", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'error with confusion matrix', 'timestamp': '2022-11-26T10:42:01Z', 'user': 'ksl0vbj3yfy5hv', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 128}),
	Document(content="Note: Hi all! Homework 9 grades have been released for all sections now. Everyone should be able to view their grades on Brightspace and their grading feedback in their Homework 9 repository on GitHub. To view your feedback, go to your Homework 9 repository on GitHub, click the drop-down menu under ‘master/main’ --> click ‘Tags’ --> click ‘regraded.’ There will be a file called “grading_output.txt” in your repository which contains the grader’s feedback along with how many points were earned for each question part. If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request to ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com . You have one week from the day grades posted to Brightspace to request a regrade. Remember to include the following information in your email: When submitting an email for a regrade request please do the following: Have a separate email for each HW regrade request Have the subject line be the following: HW# regrade request, in this case HW9 regrade request . This makes it a lot easier for us to filter the inbox and find your email. Also, a reminder to include the following information in your email: Relevant identifying information. For homework assignments, a link to your GitHub repository is needed. Section Number Grading item (e.g., homework 9) Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email) Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justifications. ", meta={'folders': ['hw9'], 'title': 'Homework 9 Grades Released!', 'timestamp': '2022-11-26T02:05:28Z', 'user': 'kskmx82xa2s4ad', 'tags': ['hw9', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 198}),
	Document(content="Question: The instructions for HW10 say that the repo should include the .gitignore file, and that we would not need to change the way that we go about adding/committing/pushing to github. However, there seems to be no .gitignore file included in the repo that I cloned from github, so my commit included the data folder. I can go ahead and delete them from the remote repository without much difficulty, but I thought people should be aware of this. Answer: If there is no .gitignore file then that is an error on our part. Students should still avoid pushing the data and may create their own .gitignore file for convenience that include the lines: data/ .idea/ .vscode/ git rm --cached -r data/ ", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'No .gitignore file included in HW10 github repo', 'timestamp': '2022-11-26T01:08:43Z', 'user': 'kyc1gk4rauf6dd', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 121}),
	Document(content="Question: I'm not really understanding what goes inside the list of class predictions and and list of true class labels. My initial assumption was that each list has a size equal to the number of data points, and each list element is the predicted or actual class (i.e., a number between 0 and num_class-1 ) the data point belongs to, respectively. Is that correct? Answer: Your understanding is correct for the homework. A side note - it is not necessary that the class labels should be in the range [0,num_class - 1]. num_class just represents the number of unique classes being predicted. In our case with the digits, the number of classes is 10 (since there are 10 digits ranging from 0 to 9). It just so happens that in our case, the range of classes goes from 0 to num_class - 1. ", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'HW 10 Problem 1 - Class predictions and true class labels', 'timestamp': '2022-11-25T19:37:10Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="Question: Are we not allowed to use any external libraries such as numpy or pandas? Or are we not allowed to use library that is related to classification?(sklearn, tensorflow) Answer: You may use other standard libraries such as numpy and pandas. Specifically, we are asking that you not use the sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix function so that you have an opportunity to code the logic of a confusion matrix yourself (although it should be fairly simple regardless). ", meta={'folders': ['hw10'], 'title': 'Homework 10 part 1', 'timestamp': '2022-11-25T07:13:13Z', 'user': 'ksl0vbj3yfy5hv', 'tags': ['hw10', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 128}),
