	Document(content="Question: Can someone help me with this one, specifically what the replacement is trying to do? Answer: Finds patterns where you have two word characters followed by an o and another word character, and replaces it with the first group (first word character), an a, the second group (second word character), and the third group (third word character). First match is 'opot', which gets replaced with 'oapt'. Second match is 'atoh', which gets replaced with 'aath'. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam Fall 2021 Regex Question', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T20:26:05Z', 'user': 'ktnb4igwbzl5e5', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 109}),
	Document(content="Question: To construct an 80% confidence interval, why are the calculations using 1.28 instead of 0.85? Answer: You want an 80% two sided interval. The percentages in the table are one sided - 0.80 of the shaded area under the z score really mean that 0.20 of the area is above the z score. If you use the 0.80 value for the two sided interval then you're throwing 0.20 on both sides resulting in a 60% two sided confidence interval. When you use score corresponding to 0.90, it means that 0.10 of the area is above the z score. When you set up the two sided confidence interval, you get a (1 - 0.10 *2 = 80%) two sided confidence interval. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2021 Question 1', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T20:05:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 100}),
	Document(content="Question: How was the feature matrix formed from the information provided? Mainly why is the last column all 1's and how was the first column calculated? Thanks in advance! Answer: In addition to the student answer, the last column is 1 because that is the coefficient that is implicitly in front of 'b' the intercept term in the regression of y = ax+b ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Question 5 A', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T19:38:43Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 99}),
	Document(content="Question:  How should I choose the df for this question to get my t-score? Answer: Since we are only calculating the confidence interval for a single set of collected samples, we use n-1 degrees of freedom where n is the number of samples. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Question Fall 2021 Exam Question 1 C', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T18:42:48Z', 'user': 'ktnb4igwbzl5e5', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 98}),
	Document(content="Question: Why is 'aly @gmail.com ' not a possible match for this problem? Thanks in advance! Answer: \d+, not at least 1 digit after the alphabetic string", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Q2 Part A', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T18:32:57Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 92}),
	Document(content="Question: Can somone walk me through how to determine the answer for this one? I feel like it relates to this slide but I dont quite understand  Answer: If you run it with regularization then you want the coefficients of the variables (x) to be smaller than the coefficients of the trained model. For example in answers C and D, the starting coefficients are higher than the trained model so we can remove that. Also, we don't care about negatives only the magnitude. So answers A and B which are left, when analyzed have smaller coefficients therefore those are the answers. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'S22 Q 3b', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T17:57:50Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 104}),
	Document(content="Question: can someone please explain what ridge regession is and what this formula does? Screenshot_2022-10-31_002619.png Answer: The following formula is most important.![image.png](/redirect/s3?bucket=uploads&prefix=paste%2Fk5b7oio0bcz3yb%2Ffd035aa375485f387bd1b8f6e1b9c435c63790b2ba500f509033d15f5b784ef1%2Fimage.png)In least square regression we only care about minimizing the sum of the squares of the residuals. In Ridge regression we modify this formula to care about not only the sum of squares of the residuals, but also our regularization parameter $$\lambda$$ multiplied by the sum of the squared *coefficients*.The result of this is that now we don't only care about the error from the model on the data, but also the complexity of the model. A more complex model that accurately predicts every point is not necessarily better than a simple model that does a pretty good job.The effectiveness, theory, and intuition of Ridge regression is covered in significantly greater depth in lecture. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'ridge regression', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T04:27:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 94}),
	Document(content="Question: Screenshot_2022-10-30_204209.png why is this d? Answer: Lambda monotonically increases as degree increases because a more complex model will always be more powerful (and thus, more prone to overfitting) than a model with a smaller degree. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'exam quesition', 'timestamp': '2022-10-31T00:44:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 105}),
	Document(content="Question: Why is the lower bound for the one-sided test in question 1D negative infinity?? Is this the case for all one-sided upper confidence intervals? Thanks in advance! Answer: Yeah. Slide 27 hypothesis notes.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 2021 Question 1D', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T21:46:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 87}),
	Document(content="Question: How do we calculate the idf? I don't really understand the solution. Answer: Really just a plug and chug. IDF is the log base 10 of the number of documents divided by the number of documents the word appears in. Check in the ngrams slideset starting from slide 9.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F21 Q6b', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T21:29:08Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 94}),
	Document(content="Question: I think they are the same type of question but I do not know how we get the answer. Thanks in advance for helping. Answer: When we do regularization (lambda != 0). We are trying to prevent overfitting by limiting the number of parameters in our models. One manifestation of that is the reduction of value of the constant coefficients in front of each X's. That said, models created with regularization should have smaller constant coefficients in front of each X's compared to those that are created without regularization. See post @300 for help on fall 2021 question 5e Hope this helps. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Question about exam 2 spring 2022 question 3 b and fall 2021 question 5 e', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T20:49:02Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 101}),
	Document(content="Question: I have a couple questions about regex I want to make sure I am interpreting some of these right \W matches like periods, commas, exclamation marks, and so on? (?=abc) - I am honetly confused on how these two work like what does it mean ' matches if “abc” is what comes next' like is it a weird look ahead variant? I have the same question about the next one. (?!abc) match.groups() 'returns all subgroups in a list' does this function return like all the groups matched in a regex, could someone provide me with an example?  Answer: so \W = matches any non word character, so yes it matches periods, commas, exclamation marks but not underscores. ?=abc gives a match if 'abc' is after the segment, so it only matches if the term abc comes right after ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'regex questions', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T20:48:37Z', 'user': 'ktnb65dyj24658', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 84}),
	Document(content="Question: Where does the (1, 2, 3) for y come from? Answer: 3rd element is y for datapoints 1-5. Stored in the form (x1, x2, y) in problem statement.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F21 Q4', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T20:18:25Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 84}),
	Document(content="Question: The bigger confidence interval percentage means a wider interval correct? Then a smaller percentage means that the interval would be narrower. Right? Another question: If we had a very low confidence interval like 40% but 85% percent of our mean fell into our interval, what does that mean and what does that tell us? The way I am thinking is that our confidence interval was much better than we were expecting. Am I completely wrong or maybe missing something? Answer: A confidence interval [l, u] means that you are x percent confident that the population parameter is captured by the interval. If you want to be more confident that your population parameter is captured, your interval intuitively needs to be larger. And vice versa. Don’t really understand what your second question means. “85% of the mean”? If your confidence interval had a confidence level of 40%, then if you ran that experiment, there’s a 40% chance that your CI will capture the population parameter based on the new sample parameters you measure. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Confidence interval question', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T19:53:31Z', 'user': 'ktnb65dyj24658', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 80}),
	Document(content="Question: On question 5, part E, why is yn 1037 and 1030? I thought yn is the measured value and ax_n +b is the estimated value from our model? Shouldn’t yn be 1041 and 1032 because they are the measured values that are given in the problem? Answer: 1037 and 1030 are what you got from part d by calculation, which is the value we predict from the model. 1041 and 1032 are from the testing data table. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2 Spring 2022 Q5', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T19:32:57Z', 'user': 'ktnb4xfj1co7ao', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="Question: For part C, can someone explain specifically why a higher degree represents a higher optimal lambda value? For part E, is a 'possible model' just anything that is within the order of coefficients in the training set and has bigger coefficient magnitudes? A more detailed explanation of why that is may also be helpful.Thanks in advance! Answer: On the regression slides, the one slide about lambdas says that higher value of lambda place the number of parameters in your model to higher importance; lower value of lambda puts minimizing error to higher importance. In the question you asked, since the problem itself is a polynomial regression. High lambda --> more parameters (x_n, where n = 1, 2, 3...), In the context of polynomials, it means more powered terms. I hope my interpretation helps.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 21 Exam 2 Q5', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T19:11:02Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 104}),
	Document(content="Question: How do we determine the df (degrees of freedom) for the t-test? Answer: df = n - 1 ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'F21 Q2(C-D)', 'timestamp': '2022-10-30T05:05:27Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 81}),
	Document(content="Question: Does anyone know the method in approaching this problem? Answer: Regularization adds a penalty on the magnitude of the slopes so if you have a slope learned from least squares without regularization $$a_1,$$ and then you add a penalty $$\lambda > 0,$$ and learn a new slope $$\tilde{a}_1$$, you will have $$|\tilde{a}_1|\leq |a_1|.$$ Does that make sense? ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring2022 Question 3(b)', 'timestamp': '2022-10-29T21:47:41Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 100}),
