	Document(content="Question: I can't figure out what, if any changes, need to be done to the code to load the GOOG.csv file. I also don't know how to normalize X in the context of this problem. If anyone could help me that would be great. Answer: I was a bit confused for awhile with this one too. To normalize X in this situation, you take the X that you got from the GOOG file, then you would treat it as your X_test, meaning you subtract the mean and divide by the standard deviation. The mean and standard deviation you would be using are the same ones you got in part 6, but this time you subtract and divide them from the X from the GOOG file. For loading the code you can basically just copy paste the lines that were used to load the Apple data, but switch the APPL.csv to GOOG.csv and all the dfs to df1. Also you don't need to split this data, so don't worry about doing that. ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Problem 2 part 8', 'timestamp': '2022-10-27T00:19:59Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 130}),
	Document(content="Question: regularize-cv.py: # Part 3 # Function to return a numpy array generated with `np.logspace` with a length # of 51 starting from 1E^-1 and ending at 1E^3 README.md: Define the range of λ to test in get_lambda_range as [1E−2.00,..., 1E3.00] . This type of logarithmic scale is common for regularization. You should use the numpy function np.logspace to define this array (Hint: Use 51 points as num, 1e-2 as the starting value, and 1e+3 as the final value of the sequence). See the documentation on np.logspace here: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.logspace.html . The lower bound specified for lambda is 1E-2 in README.md, and 1E-1 in regularize-cv.py. Answer: Yes, it is a typo in the code; @255 - Use what's in the README ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Homework 7 possible typo in the code comment', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T23:43:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
	Document(content="Question: What X value are we using when plotting y and y_hat, since the X we used is a matrix, and y/y_hat is a vector. Answer: Both y and y_hat are time-series data. Ideally you would want to plot them against time, but since we are just comparing y and y_hat (and seeing if your predicted values were accurate) and don't really care about the days themselves, you can just plot them like plot(y)plot(y_hat) By default, matplotlib uses 0,1,2,3,..., (len(plotted data) -1) as the x values. This works because y and y_hat correspond to each other (that is, the first value in y_hat is the predicted stock price for a particular day and the first value in y is the actual stock price for that particular day and so on). ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW7 Problem 2 Part 8', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T22:03:35Z', 'user': 'ke4p3obb60q4i5', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 126}),
	Document(content="Question: The instructions say to graph y and y_hat on the same plot, but y_hat is based on a normalized X while y is straight from the data. Are we supposed to normalize y as well? Should we be using the same normalize_train and normalize_test functions for y? When I try using these functions, my y and y_hat have very different y intercepts. I'm just unsure how we are supposed to go about graphing these together. Answer: You do not normalize y. Your y values come directly from the data, while your y_hat values are generated by invoking the .predict() method on the model you found to be best in part 7, with your input being your normalized X matrix. ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'HW7 Problem 2 Part 8 Graphing', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T21:59:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="Question: Once you obtain the p-value from a t statistic, would you divide the p-value by 2 if it is a one-sided test? Or is the p-value for one side and you multiply it by 2 for a two-sided test? Answer: For one-sided test, the p-value will be the area at one tail while for a two-sided test, the p-value will be the area at both tails. This is true irrespective of whether you do a z-test or a t-test. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 't-test question', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T20:13:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 95}),
	Document(content="Question: What matrix manipulation will we need to perform for the exam? Will we be required to transpose and take the inverse of matrices by hand or will we only need to perform matrix multiplication? Answer: Any matrix algebra covered in class in the slides or notebook are fair game on the exam. So this includes matrix addition, subtraction, multiplication, dot products, and transpose. However, you will not be expected to invert matrices by hand since the method for this was not covered in class. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 2 linear algebra required calculations', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T19:47:00Z', 'user': 'ktnb6hg6fwi8a', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
