	Document(content="Question: I don't understand why X_test and y_test are used as input variables for the error function we are required to write. Are we adding error in X and y using model? # Evaluate the MSE on the test set mse = error(X_test, y_test, model) Answer: You need to use X_test to predict y values with your model and then compute the error between the predicted y values and the actual y values. ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'mse', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T01:34:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 118}),
	Document(content="Question: In Part 8, when we plot the 2nd graph as shown in word document outline, what would be labels for x and y axes. And what would be the title for the graph? Because in the outline (question 4 of problem 2), it just has the plot and a legend saying which plot is the actual and which is the prediction and there are no titles or labels for the axes. Answer: For part 8, same preprocessing steps used for 'APPL.csv' should be applied to 'GOOG.csv'. Thus, the code provided in 'regularize-cv.py', containing 7 steps for processing the 'APPL.csv' file, can be used again for the 'GOOG.csv' file. When fitting the 'GOOG.csv' file, target variable and feature vectors should be the following: 1) Target variable 'y' is generated by shifting the values in Close column by 1. 2) Attribute vectors correspond to all the remaining columns in 'GOOG.csv', except for the Close column and the Date column. (The procedure is the same as when the 'APPL.csv' file was processed.) When drawing a plot in Part 8, just plot target variable, y , and predicted value, y_hat . There is no need to explicitly designate the labels for x and y axes. For example, it is recommended to use the below code block to generate the plot. ''' plt.figure() plt.plot(y_hat, label='prediction') plt.plot(y, label='actual') plt.legend(fontsize=10, loc='upper left') plt.title('Google Test') plt.show() ''' The title of the plot can be anything. It does not necessarily have to be 'Google Test' as given in the code block above. However, the label of true target_variable and the predicted target_variable should be clearly named so that we can recognize which plot corresponds to which value. ", meta={'folders': ['hw7'], 'title': 'Hw#7 Problem 2 Part 8', 'timestamp': '2022-10-26T01:18:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw7', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 119}),
