	Document(content="Question: I'm working through the test cases for problem 3, and in particular the test case where the word apprentice is used more than once are giving me some trouble. For example, test case 'Although Maul was an apprentice to sith apprentice Sidious, he is not half the sith lord he wanted to be.', I'm having trouble only replacing the second occurrence of apprentice, while leaving the first apprentice untouched. For example , my output would be 'Although Maul was an Darth to sith Darth Sidious, he is not half the sith lord he wanted to be.' Is there a way to specify which occurrence of apprentice that needs to be replace when using substitution, or is there another way to approach this issue? Thanks in advance! Answer: The best way to do this is to make your regular expression only match 'sith apprentice' so your substitution is always safe. ", meta={'folders': ['hw6'], 'title': 'HW6: Problem 3 Case Question', 'timestamp': '2022-10-16T19:54:20Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw6', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
	Document(content="Question: My regular expression works perfectly fine and verifies the correct strings, but when I try to access them in VS Code using (in my case) p.group(k) where k is the group, I get an error like below. I thought that .group() would adjust based on the input? Answer: You can use groups only if you have a Match object (that is, you call something like p.search() or any method that matches the string for your regex pattern, where p is your compiled regex). As an example: if p is your compiled regex: matched = p.search(searchstring)# matched is a match object, so you can do something like this: matched_group_1 = matched.group(1)# Code below returns an error because p is just your compiled regex string and not a result of searching a particular string for that regex patternmatched_err = p.group(1) ", meta={'folders': ['hw6'], 'title': 'Problems with \'match\'.group(k) in VS Code', 'timestamp': '2022-10-16T04:51:06Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw6', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 121}),
