	Document(content="Question: Hello  In Problem 2 statement, it says that' In this problem, consider the following dataset of the number of points by which a sports team won in its last 11 games: [3, -3, 3, 12, 15, -16, 17, 19, 23, -24, 32, 10, -4] It says that the dataset is the number of points by which a sports team won in its last 11 games, but what I count for this list is 13. I'm wondering which value we should use for the sample size? Thank you! Answer: That's a typo on our end, sorry about that. 13 is the sample size. ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW5 Problem 2 sample size', 'timestamp': '2022-10-07T04:51:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="Question: I just wanna make sure I'm doing the correct calculations here. The equation they give us to find p is 'p = norm.cdf(z_c)'. This equation only covers the area under half of the curve where 'p = 2 * stats.norm.cdf(-abs(z))' covers the whole thing. With this we need to divide the given a values in half for comparing to the first equation? Also for the write up, do I use the p value from 'p = norm.cdf(z_c)' or from ''p = 2 * stats.norm.cdf(-abs(z))' ? Answer: The alpha values 0.10 and 0.05 given are used to compare your p-values to. If your p-value is less than these alpha values, then your results are statistically significant at that level. You don't divide alpha by 2. The reason why the p-value doubled is because the alternate hypothesis is that the true mean is different than the sample mean. If the alt hypothesis was that the true mean was greater than or less than the sample, then it would be the one-tailed value. ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Homework 5 question 1', 'timestamp': '2022-10-07T02:33:19Z', 'user': 'ktnb63ymkyx5xg', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 113}),
	Document(content="Question: When calculating the p-value using the z score, should I use the two-tail method or the one-tail? In other words, should I multiply by two as shown in the lecture slides, or not as shown in the read me file? Answer: Brian is correct, but you should consider why. We're trying to prove that the mean is not equal to some value, but we don't specify higher or lower. Thus we need to check both cases (two sided). ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Homework 5 Problem 1', 'timestamp': '2022-10-07T02:12:57Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 105}),
	Document(content="Question: For Problem 4, Q2 in homework 5, I was able to find a p value for the given problem and a confidence interval. How do I work back and find the percent confidence from this point? Is p related to 1 - (1-c)/2? Answer: Consider a graphical representation of a p value. It's the area on the tail(s) of a normal distribution. The confidence level is the opposite, the area not in the tail (s). From this you see the relationship between the two values. ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Finding percent confidence from p-value', 'timestamp': '2022-10-07T01:15:15Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
