	Document(content="Question: For HW 5 problem 1 I am confused on what the code needs to output. Since there is no output template we have to match, do we just output the answers in anyway we find convenient? For example, for problem 1 part 2, would we just write code that calculates the values such as sample mean and sample error, and then have a print statement print out the answers? Answer: The important thing is your write-up, we'll just verify your code also produces the same results as your write up. Just have it print out your work. ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5 Output Confusion', 'timestamp': '2022-10-06T20:37:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 107}),
	Document(content="Question: For HW 5 Problem 1, is the sample size 2 since we have 2 data sets, or would the sample size be the 3000 students? I was confused on which one since that would change what test I would use. Answer: There are two datasets with multiple samples in each of them. You would consider the sample size of each dataset (sample size of engagement0 being the number of samples in the engagement0.txt file and sample size of engagement1 being the number of samples in the engagement1.txt file); you would have two different sample sizes for each of the two datasets. ", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'Sample Size', 'timestamp': '2022-10-06T20:24:51Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 109}),
	Document(content="Question: I don't understand how to calculate the t-score without a given population mean. Answer: You do not need the population mean on problem 2. Since we are calculating the values for a confidence interval, the t-value is calculated using the given confidence interval. The formula to calculate t is t_c = t.ppf(1-(1-c) / 2, df)", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'What value to use for population mean for problem 2', 'timestamp': '2022-10-06T04:40:36Z', 'user': 'k84uo8xrdu078p', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 137}),
	Document(content="Question: I am trying to calculate the t - value. I know this is the formula. However, I am struggling to understand what mu will be here. In prob 1, we were given the value of 0.75 but in this question, we aren't given the true population parameter. What should I use in place of mu? Answer: You do not need the population mean on problem 2. Since we are calculating the values for a confidence interval, the t-value is calculated using the given confidence interval. The formula to calculate t is t_c = t.ppf(1-(1-c) / 2, df)", meta={'folders': ['hw5'], 'title': 'HW 5, Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2022-10-06T04:23:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw5', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 130}),
