	Document(content="Question: When is the law of large numbers applicable and what does it mean exactly Answer: The Law of Large Numbers states that the sample mean will approach the population mean as n gets large (approaches infinity) ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Quick question law of large numbers', 'timestamp': '2022-09-28T13:39:05Z', 'user': 'ktnb65dyj24658', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 135}),
	Document(content="Question: Will we have confidence intervals, t-distributions, or t-tests on the exam? (Slides 16-27 of the Week 5 slides). I do not remember covering them in class or in today's exam review. Answer: No, confidence intervals will not be in exam 1. Only slides 1-15 of that slide deck relate to this exam. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Exam 1 Content Question', 'timestamp': '2022-09-27T22:50:28Z', 'user': 'ktnb40rmxba37m', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 169}),
	Document(content="Question: when we say the sample mean is N(u, σ^2/n), what does the big 'N' mean? I don't think I totally understand the concept. Answer: The big N refers to the normal distribution (or Gaussian distribution) that is centered at the mean $$\mu$$ with sample variance $$ \frac{{\sigma}^2}{n}$$. CLT basically states that the distribution of the sample means tends to a normal distribution with the above parameters as n (the number of samples) gets very large", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Central Limit Theorem', 'timestamp': '2022-09-27T21:41:13Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 149}),
	Document(content="Question: What if the significance level and p-value are equal, say both come to the value of 0.05? What would happen in this case? Would it just be inconclusive or the probability of this happening is too low to be considered? Answer: That's an edge case if $$\text{p-value} = \alpha$$. Based on slide 10 of hypothesis testing, our convention is to consider $$\text{p-value} \leq \alpha$$ as anomalous (the case where we reject the null hypothesis). ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'p-value and significance level', 'timestamp': '2022-09-27T14:53:39Z', 'user': 'ke6hswn31sc3ll', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 154}),
	Document(content="Question: How do we know keeping variance constant and increasing n would reduce the standard error of the hypothesis test? Answer: The standard error is given by $$SE = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}$$ where $${\sigma}^2$$ is the variance and n, the number of samples. So by keeping the variance constant and increasing the number of samples, the standard error would decrease. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Question 6F', 'timestamp': '2022-09-27T05:18:32Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 136}),
	Document(content="Question: How does the 68/95/99.7 rule relate to p-value? How do we use this rule to get a p-value from the z-score? Answer: The 68/95/99.7 rule just states that what percentage of the area lies within a z-score of 1, 2, and 3 respectively. The corresponding 2 tailed p-value is just the opposite proportion - ~0.32 for a z-score of 1, ~0.05 for a z-score of 2, and ~0.03 for a z-score of 3. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'p-value?', 'timestamp': '2022-09-27T00:00:52Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="Question: For questions like this will we be given a p-value chart. If not, how do we convert the z-score to p-value manually? Answer: @163, just know the 68/95/99.7 rule and if there’s anything that requires a table they will provide it", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'p-value chart?', 'timestamp': '2022-09-26T23:51:28Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 123}),
	Document(content="Question: For the solution to this problem it states for increasing n1, n2, n3 but shows n1 twice. Which graph is supposed to be the n3 graph? Answer: If you increase the sample size, the two tails shrink. So the tallest one would be the one with the larger sample size. ", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Fall 22 Exam Problem 8B', 'timestamp': '2022-09-26T23:28:46Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 108}),
	Document(content="Question: Shouldn't this be a since the p value is 0.05 which is less than 0.25? Answer: The alpha is the point at which you decide if your pval is low enough to reject the null hypothesis. If your alpha is greater than your pval, then that means your pval is significant - that’s why at all points where alpha is greater than 0.05 is when your pval of 0.05 is significant.", meta={'folders': ['exam'], 'title': 'Spring 2022 Question 6 d', 'timestamp': '2022-09-26T23:12:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['exam', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 117}),
