	Document(content="Question: The readme file states that we should use a print statement inside the box filter function to output a message in case the box length and the input length are not the same in the box filter function. However, because through my code the box filter function ends up being called multiple times in the stencil function, due to the stencil function iterating through a list, the same print statement regarding the lengths ends up being printed multiple times. Of course, this happens when I change the length L on my own to check what my output would be. Am I doing something wrong with my code or is this how it is supposed to be in case of the lengths being different? Thanks Answer: I am having trouble following your high level description of how your code works. Can you come to office hours tomorrow (best) or post a private message with your code? ", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'Hw4 Problem 2', 'timestamp': '2022-09-22T00:45:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 124}),
	Document(content="Question: For problem 1 on HW 4, there is an additional print statement on the problem 1 file that is not mentioned in the expected output of the Read Me file. Should we remove this print statement to make the output the same as the expected output stated in the Read Me file, or should we leave the file as is? Answer: If it's given, leave it as it is. ", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'HW4 Problem 1 Results', 'timestamp': '2022-09-21T22:28:12Z', 'user': 'ktnb4jkg9mi5ib', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 129}),
	Document(content="Question: If the only parameter passed to ret_fun is x, how is ret_fun supposed to access the fun and num_repeated in order to call fun on x that many times? Shouldn't fun and num_repeated be passed to ret_fun as well? Answer: This is the concept of 'closure', when we define a function inside of a different function it has access to the local values of the enclosing function(s) at the time of them being called!```{python}def create_adder(a: int): def add_a(b: int): return b + a return add_aadd_5 = create_adder(5)print(add_5(10), 'This is 5 + 10 == 15')```What's even weirder is that you can mess with these enclosed variables and therefore give your functions state.```{python}def list_printer(l: list): def inner_printer(x): l.append('new') print(l, x) return inner_printermy_printer = list_printer(['old'])my_printer(': This will print ['old', 'new']')my_printer(': This will print ['old', 'new', 'new']')my_printer(': This will print ['old', 'new', 'new', 'new']')```Things get even weirder with the usage of the `nonlocal` keyword in Python, but now we're so far off the beaten path so I won't ramble on :). ", meta={'folders': ['hw4'], 'title': 'HW4 prob4 only passing x into ret_fun', 'timestamp': '2022-09-21T19:49:36Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw4', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 115}),
