	Document(content="Question: I wrote all of my code for problem one, but when I run it I get the error message 'IndexError: only integers, slices (`:`), ellipsis (`...`), numpy.newaxis (`None`) and integer or boolean arrays are valid indices' it says the problem in in the line 'num_samples += hist[i]' why am I getting this message? Answer: for i in hist This means that each i is an element of hist, and not the index itself - therefore you cannot really index hist using i, since i refers to the element in the histogram as opposed to the index of an element in the histogram. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'error message in norm_histogram function', 'timestamp': '2022-09-16T16:54:24Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 112}),
	Document(content="Question: When looking at the output for find_min the README says the output should be `{0: -0.010112286832993561, 7: -0.01011096946216514}` and then goes on to say the output will be checked up to four decimal places. in the list 'l' the first 12 positions of the list are the same when compared to the 4th decimal place. How can index 0 and 7 be the correct answer? Do i need to compare the whole float before rounded to 4 decimals? Answer: From the README: find_min is a generic function that takes a list of numbers and returns the two smallest number in that list along with their index. In this example 0 is the index of the minimum and 7 is the index of the next smallest number. I believe you need to compare the whole float to figure out what the two smallest numbers are, and then the answer will be checked to four decimal places. ", meta={'folders': ['logistics', 'hw3'], 'title': 'find_min correct output doesn\'t make sense?', 'timestamp': '2022-09-16T16:04:30Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 110}),
