	Document(content="Question: Hello In problem1, it ask us to make a normal histogram. The sample size given is 1000, but how do we know the number of bins. In the test case, the number of bins is 10. Is it got from the input variable 'histo' since the histo is defined as 'histo = plt.hist(data, 10, (lo, hi))[0]'. If the ten is gotten from here, how can I unpack the parameter and assign the 10 to another variable so that I could use this number for calculation? Thank you. Answer: The target of this problem is to determine the best number of bins by calculating and comparing the j value. For the first part, norm_histogram(), the input is already a histogram, you just need to convert it from histogram of number to histogram of probabilities. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Prob1', 'timestamp': '2022-09-16T04:44:40Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="Question: I am trying to write the sweep_n function and am getting this error:  There shouldn't be type rectagle anywhere in the code. Where could this be coming from? Answer: This is most likely because of what matplotlib.pyplot.hist (or plt.hist) returns - it returns a tuple in this format (histogram, bins, patches). So, when you want the histogram from this, you just need the first element of the tuple, and not anything else. In your case, the histogram is hist[0], while hist itself is the tuple returned by matplotlib.pyplot.hist. https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.hist.html - Here is the documentation for this function if you want to know more! ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 prob1 \'Rectangle\' error', 'timestamp': '2022-09-16T03:52:58Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 94}),
