	Document(content="Question: Can someone explain the meaning of the normalized histogram list? Is each element always one-thousandth of the corresponding element in the normal histogram list, or are they divided by the sample size? Or is it just a coincidence in the example for problem 1 in GitHub? Answer: The function to normalize a histogram converts a histogram of counts to a histogram of probabilities. That is, each bin represents the probability that a random point from the data occurs between the edges of the bin.Please reference slide 13 from the histogram lecture notes, this topic is fair game for exams. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Prob1 Normalized Histogram', 'timestamp': '2022-09-15T15:04:54Z', 'user': 'kz5ooe8hhh2nz', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 139}),
	Document(content="Question: This is the result given to us: And this is my result: For the last one, there is a slightly off for final decimals, would this be considered as points off or margin of error. And is it normal for my computer to take several minutes to run through? Answer: We only check the first four decimal places for this problem, so you would not get any points off for this. As for the runtime, the program does take some time to run, so it should be fine. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Result for Problem 2 is slightly off', 'timestamp': '2022-09-15T04:10:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 141}),
	Document(content="Question: I calculated J using the formula given in lecture. However, my output has some decimals off compared to -0.010095851785675588. Is this a problem? Answer: The number of samples seems to be wrong in your image (unless it's getting cut off somewhere); it's supposed to be 1000, not 100 - you can check if you are correctly calculating /returning the total number of samples in your function. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'J Value', 'timestamp': '2022-09-14T22:34:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 130}),
	Document(content="Question: I'm trying to calculate J right now and I keep getting a value of -0.05056143416496779 instead of -0.010095851785675588. Am I able to have someone check my code? I used the equation from slide 19. Answer: Also be very careful with operator precedence! `m + 1 / (m - 1) * w` will be parsed like `m + (1 / (m - 1) * w)` which is not what you want. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'J calculated wrong', 'timestamp': '2022-09-14T17:32:10Z', 'user': 'ktlz1u25brv5lz', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 143}),
	Document(content="Question: I installed numpy through VS code (on Windows) and I'm having trouble using it. I can see the file in my file explorer so I'm pretty sure it's installed just fine, but I think it's not in the path. I've attached a screenshot of the message I get when I run the code for the first problem. Is anyone able to help me?  Answer: There are many possible problems. First, do you have multiple versions of python or pip installed? Sometimes, pip and pip3 have different addresses to keep packages. If your VS code has a package manager (I believe it has), go to check it or reinstall the package from the package manager. In the terminal, use pip list and pip3 list to check the package installed. The best way you can try now is pip uninstall numpy and pip install numpy again. It should check everything needed. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Problem with numpy in VS code', 'timestamp': '2022-09-14T04:11:12Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 145}),
	Document(content="Question: How long should we expect to see a response to a submitted regrade request? Thanks in advance! Answer: Given the amount of regrade requests for HW1 we are hoping to finish most of them by the end of the week or the beginning of next week. ", meta={'folders': ['logistics'], 'title': 'Regrade Request', 'timestamp': '2022-09-14T01:40:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['logistics', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="Question: I can't get the code to 'read' the input.txt file. It only works under the condition of setting the file name as: './homework-3-f22-NAME/input.txt' How can I set the local txt file to just 'input.txt'? Below is the error message I got: FileNotFoundError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: 'input.txt' Answer: If you are using ecegrid terminal, make sure you open it in the directory of your workspace or change the root to that directory. The Unix/Linus system will start looking for the file from the root address of your terminal. If you are using an IDE with a project manager, including the input file into the project may be another solution. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Python unable to find local text file', 'timestamp': '2022-09-14T01:39:07Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 127}),
