	Document(content="Question: Hello, as titled. I've gone to my github repository and verified that my homework 1 was graded. However, my brightspace page for homework is still 0%. Is there something wrong with the survey I filled out on the beginning of the semester? Answer: There is a very high likelihood that is the case. Please email a GTA with your GitHub account name and Purdue username and they can check for your score and update the survey response list accordingly. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1', 'other'], 'title': 'Homework 1 Graded on GitHub but Has Score of 0 on BrightSpace', 'timestamp': '2022-09-13T00:52:22Z', 'user': 'kggrdlpzeke3je', 'tags': ['hw1', 'other', 'student'], 'likes': 3, 'views': 120}),
	Document(content="Question: I was trying to download the module using the command 'python3 -mpip install --user scipy' and the results shows failure 'WARNING: You are using pip version 19.2.3, however version 22.2.2 is available.You should consider upgrading via the 'pip install --upgrade pip' command.' Answer: Please try to upgrade 'pip' via the command `pip install --upgrade pip`After that, try to install 'scipy' via `python3 -mpip install --user scipy`If it still does not work, please let me know the error. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'numpy module download fail', 'timestamp': '2022-09-13T00:42:37Z', 'user': 'ke4p486g5cx530', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 147}),
	Document(content="Question: Are we supposed to submit anything in Brightspace for our homeworks? From my understanding, all we had to do was push the code up to Github and then the grades would be entered into Brightspace, but I saw a homework 1 submission page on Brightspace that says 'overdue'. I want to check whether or not we're supposed to submit anything to this submission page. Answer: No need to submit anything on Brightspace for any of the homeworks. Once you push your code and verify that it looks correct on GitHub, you are done and the homework has been submitted. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Homework Submissions Brightspace', 'timestamp': '2022-09-12T17:37:41Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 2, 'views': 114}),
	Document(content="Question: The norm_histogram description states that the function should return 'a tuple that contains a list and a int, i.e. ([...], int)'. On the README instructions, however, the example of a correct output for the 'number of samples' shows a float (as shown below). Is this a typo? The instructions on README: norm_histogram runs correctly then the output will be histogram: [104. 96. 94. 79. 108. 92. 114. 109. 121. 83.] normalized histogram: [0.104, 0.096, 0.094, 0.079, 0.108, 0.092, 0.114, 0.109, 0.121, 0.083] number of samples: 1000.0 Answer: Don't worry about it! The comparison between two tuples: ([...], 1000)==([...], 1000.0) will be True in Python.But you can transform the num_sample (e.g., 1000.0) to an int (e.g., 1000) if you want. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'HW3 Problem1 Wrong Data Type', 'timestamp': '2022-09-10T22:21:08Z', 'user': 'isuhgx9uuxc1r1', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 159}),
	Document(content="Question: Can I assume that there will always have a 1000 sample size or that the input file for the auto grader will always be named input.txt? Answer: The sample size will NOT always be 1000.For the 'input.txt', don't worry about it! Because we will not use it during grading.Generally, we will not use your code below： `if __name__ == '__main__': `which means, we will not use your code as the main script during grading.As we said in README.md,The ` if __name__ == '__main__'` line in Problem1.py is a useful way to write tests for your code: this is code that will _only_ run if you run this file as the main script; **if this file is included from another script, this test code will not run**. ", meta={'folders': ['hw3'], 'title': 'Hw 3 Problem One', 'timestamp': '2022-09-10T20:09:16Z', 'user': 'ktnb8chh43f2xw', 'tags': ['hw3', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 158}),
	Document(content="Note: Hi all, Homework 1 grades have been released for all sections now. All students, can view their grading feedback in their Homework 1 repository on GitHub. To view your feedback, go to your Homework 1 repository on GitHub, click the drop down menu under 'main' --> click 'Tags' --> click 'graded.' There will be a file called grading_output.txt in your repository with the output of the grading script specifying which test cases you passed and the number of points they were worth. Note that homeworks are generally graded using test cases. We run your code on a number of test cases (these test cases are visible to you in the grading_output.txt file) and assign points based on the test cases your code passes. Each test case is worth a different number of points depending on its difficulty. If you believe an error has been made in grading, please send a regrade request to ece20875.purdue.university@gmail.com . You have one week from the day grades are posted to Brightspace to request a regrade. Remember to include the following information in your email: Relevant identifying information. For homeworks, a link to your GitHub repository is needed. Section Number Grading item (e.g., homework 1) Purdue email (if not sent from a Purdue email) Your reasoning or explanation for a regrade, with specific details and justification pointing to the README. When submitting an email for a regrade request please do the following: 1. Have a separate email for each HW 2. Have the subject line be the following: HW# regrade request (it makes it a lot easier for us to filter the inbox and find your email). As usual, feel free to post on Piazza with any additional questions :-) ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Homework 1 Grades Released', 'timestamp': '2022-09-10T15:22:28Z', 'user': 'kskmxecspaq4i1', 'tags': ['hw1', 'instructor-note'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 235}),
	Document(content="Question: I can see my grade in bright space, but I can't find where to go to see why I got the grade I did. I would like to understand why I got the grade I did, so I can do better next time. Answer: See @77 If you did not pass a certain test case, you can try running it on your code to see the reason it did not pass. If you feel like there was an error in grading, feel free to submit a regrade request (again see @77 for details on doing this) ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Reasoning HW 1', 'timestamp': '2022-09-10T15:01:24Z', 'user': 'ktnb8chh43f2xw', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 131}),
