	Document(content="Question: What is the command to run the python test files in the git bash terminal? I am able to edit the files and push them to GitHub, however I don't know how to run the test files to see if they are correct. Answer: Make sure you're in your project directory containing the test files and enter python3 filename.py where filename is the name of the test file. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Running Test Code', 'timestamp': '2022-09-07T00:24:30Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 145}),
	Document(content="Question: If the day is the same, we need to put whoever is older as the definition for the day in the final dictionary. Do we need to compare month and year or is comparing whichever year is older fine? In other words do we need to consider duplicates who are also born in the same year? resulting in our code having to compare the specific month too? Answer: No, we just need to compare the year. If the day is the same, there will be no test case where duplicates have same year as well. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': '\'Who is older\' clarification for HW2', 'timestamp': '2022-09-05T17:18:52Z', 'user': 'keuahk7t7pc1oq', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 169}),
	Document(content="Question:  I understand that there aren't any replicating keys in Python dictionaries, and I also understand that if that key is entered twice into the dictionary the value would just be the newer one. I'm confused then by this 2nd test case. Why isn't Elon's information the value for 28 rather than Bill's? (Test case 1 is here just for reference since it makes sense with my understanding. Helen comes next into the dictionary but the key for Helen is the same as Jack's and thus the output for the value of key '14' would just be Helen's information). Any help is appreciated thanks!! Answer: Bill is older than Elon, so Bill replaces Elon in the dictionary. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Conflicting replacements in dict ???', 'timestamp': '2022-09-05T05:14:49Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 157}),
	Document(content="Question: When calculating age for Problem 2, the second test case shows Stive and Bill's ages as 67 even though Bill would technically be 66 (because his birthday is in November and hasn't happened yet). Just to clarify, that means we only have to consider the year (and not the month/day) when calculating age right? Answer: See the README for clarification here. For this problem you can just calculate age as `2022 - year`. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 Age', 'timestamp': '2022-09-04T20:49:09Z', 'user': 'ke4p3qyfq0e4l8', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 173}),
	Document(content="Question: Are we allowed to have multiple return statements in one function? Specifically for Problem 1 in HW 2 when returning an empty list. Answer: Yes, you can. Make sure you have only one return statement executed during each call. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW 2 Multiple return statements in function', 'timestamp': '2022-09-03T20:49:44Z', 'user': 'ktnb4xfj1co7ao', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 170}),
	Document(content="Question: I don't understand how the first bin could have 0 in the answer here: since the lower bound is -5 and the upper bound is 10, wouldnt the data of -5 fall in the first bin? My answer that came out was the same but with '1' in the first bin. Answer: The problem states to throw out all data >= the upper bound and ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'HW2 test case 1 answer question', 'timestamp': '2022-09-03T18:24:43Z', 'user': 'jqpzjprd1742t8', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 177}),
	Document(content="Question: In the description of problem 1, this is the description given for how to calculate values in each bin. However, when testing with the test programs provided, in order to get the same values as were shown I had treat the range as (b + i*w, b + (i+1)*w). What is the correct range for each bin's values? Answer: To add to the student answer, you must trim the values equal to the upper and lower bounds as well.The correct description is the one in the README, likely your program didn't throw out the values in data equal to the lower bound. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Values for each bin', 'timestamp': '2022-09-03T15:58:29Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 159}),
	Document(content="Question: For homework 2 problem 2, the assignment states ' Caution : if there is a duplication among dates, the value of date_to_all corresponding to the duplicated date should be the tuple of values that contain (month, year, age) information of an individual who is the OLDEST' Is a duplicated date the day of the month that is duplicated if the months are different? Answer: It is the day of the month. ", meta={'folders': ['hw2'], 'title': 'Duplication among dates clarification', 'timestamp': '2022-09-03T15:20:19Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw2', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 147}),
	Document(content="Question: I submitted one more file to GitHub, how can I delete it? Answer: You can click on the .idea folder, and then in the top right corner, click the three dots and click 'delete directory'. Scroll to the bottom of the screen, and press commit changes. [Zhirui] You can also delete the file locally, then do git add -A, then commit and push as normal. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'How to delete a file on GitHub', 'timestamp': '2022-09-02T20:53:01Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="Question: Hello guys I'm just wondering that in homework 1, if we will write code to ask user to input a value, or we will just use the variable 'number' provided and changing value by adjust the value of this variable before running each test. Answer: There's no input from the user. You just change the value of the variable before running each test ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Input questions', 'timestamp': '2022-09-02T12:45:11Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 157}),
	Document(content="Question: I just summit problem 2, and it shows that there is a deletion from the original code. Not sure if I accidently delete something? Answer: It looks like you are viewing the changes between commits rather than just the current version of your repository, so you are probably fine. This kind of view is to help identify exactly what lines of code have been changed between each commit, which can be useful especially if your code breaks between different commits. [Joseph] To expand on this, it looks like you deleted a blank line. Don't worry about it! [Zhirui] What you are seeing is a diff , which is roughly how we do source control when we don't have git. Also check out the man page . ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Code deletion', 'timestamp': '2022-09-01T20:39:18Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 150}),
	Document(content="Question: I'm just wondering if the lecture during the week of Thanksgiving break will be recorded. If not, could they be? I believe there is only one lecture that week. Answer: The lectures will not be recorded, but people who missed lectures can come to their respective instructor's office hours for questions and review. ", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Thanksgiving week Lectures', 'timestamp': '2022-09-01T17:40:32Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 163}),
	Document(content="Question: is there a way to actually submit the homework or do we just push it through to Github so the files update and that's it? Answer: You can just push the final homework files to GitHub and you should be good to go.", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Submit hw 1', 'timestamp': '2022-09-01T17:33:37Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 169}),
	Document(content="Question: I finished my code for question 1 of homework 1 and when type git commit it says 'author identity unknown.' Why is it doing this? Answer: Have you set your identity on Git? If you have not, type in: git config --global user.email 'your github email here'git config --global user.name 'your name goes here' in the terminal. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Problem with git commands', 'timestamp': '2022-08-31T21:16:05Z', 'user': 'ktnb46azbvi3u8', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 158}),
	Document(content="Question: I finished the homework using python's built in math library, but was recommended to use Numpy. I downloaded Anaconda to get Numpy for the homework assignments, but whenever I try to run something using the correct interpreter with numpy (Python 3.9.12 'anaconda3') it spits out a long error message ending in Original error was: DLL load failed while importing _multiarray_umath: The specified module could not be found. Answer: Have you added Anaconda3 to the PATH variable? If you are on a Windows system, you could see if C:\\Users\<your username here>\AppData\Local\Continuum\Anaconda3\Scripts\C:\\Users\<your username here>\AppData\Local\Continuum\Anaconda3\Library\bin (or wherever the path to your installation of Anaconda is) is added to your PATH variable or not. Side note - you don't have to install Anaconda to get NumPy - you could install NumPy using pip install numpy in your terminal. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Error using Numpy with VSCode', 'timestamp': '2022-08-31T20:57:22Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="Question: Can I get the updated discord link as it always says link is invalid. Answer: https://discord.gg/V8KqVXJ7 This link should work. ", meta={'folders': ['other'], 'title': 'Discord', 'timestamp': '2022-08-31T16:15:46Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['other', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 139}),
	Document(content="Question: I'm done with Homework Part 1 and I just don't know how to push now. I've watched the video on Brightspace, and it didn't help. Can someone help with Replit or do I need to use another coding space? Answer: I think this document can be helpful. Instructions we provide are geared towards coding locally. [Joseph] I'd echo the sentiment that coding locally will be helpful in this course. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'How to Push from Replit', 'timestamp': '2022-08-30T23:54:24Z', 'user': 'ktlz1u25brv5lz', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="Question: Hello, I was using Github previously for my own projects and I had a user. Apparently my PC was logged in to terminal with that user instead of the one I created for school. I wrote the new one's info on the github registration form so TA's logged that user to Github classroom but I was somehow able to push changes using my personal Github account. Would it be a problem if I push through another github account that is not the one I stated in the form. It succesfully pushed changes by the way. Answer: Hm, did your changes only go to your homework repo? If it was to a different repository we have a problem, otherwise it's almost certainly fine. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'I accidentally pushed hw1 through another user', 'timestamp': '2022-08-30T22:28:04Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 171}),
	Document(content="Question: Hello, Are we allowed to take the Zeller Formula code entirely(and modify a little) on GeeksforGeeks as long as we give them credit in comments? Answer: See @26. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Homework 1 q 2 Zeller Formula', 'timestamp': '2022-08-30T21:17:16Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 0, 'views': 151}),
	Document(content="Question: I've almost completed the code for homework 1, but I can't figure out how to commit and push it because the terminal on VSCode doesn't recognize the git commands. I've tried installing Git Bash, but I can't use any git commands there either. Is there anything else I can do? Answer: If you are using Vs code, you can use VS code GitHub extension. You can always use the terminal (including the Vs code terminal), but make sure your terminal is open in the correct folder. The git commands only work in the cloned repository. ", meta={'folders': ['hw1'], 'title': 'Can\'t Submit Homework 1 on Visual Studio Code', 'timestamp': '2022-08-30T21:06:34Z', 'user': '', 'tags': ['hw1', 'student'], 'likes': 1, 'views': 163}),
